│ incorrect because it doesn't properly handle NaN inputs when │
│ the `nnan` (no NaNs) fast-math flag is present on the        │
│ `llvm.fabs.f16` call.\n\nLet's trace the execution with a    │
│ QNaN input (`0xH7E00`) for `%x`:\n\n**Original IR:**\n1.     │
│ `%copysign.x = call nnan half @llvm.fabs.f16(half %x)`:      │
│ Since `%x` is a NaN and the `nnan` flag is present, the      │
│ result `%copysign.x` is `poison`.\n2.  `%ord = fcmp ord half │
│ %x, 0xH0000`: `fcmp ord` checks if both operands are         │
│ \"ordered\" (not NaN). Since `%x` is a NaN, this comparison  │
│ returns `false`.\n3.  `%cmp = fcmp uge half %copysign.x,     │
│ 0xH7C00`: The input `%copysign.x` is `poison`, so the result │
│ `%cmp` is also `poison`.\n4.  `%and = select i1 %ord, i1     │
│ %cmp, i1 false`: The condition `%ord` is `false`, so the     │
│ `select` instruction returns its third operand, which is     │
│ `false`.\n\nThe function correctly returns `false` for a NaN │
│ input.\n\n**Transformed IR:**\n1.  `%copysign.x = call nnan  │
│ half @llvm.fabs.f16(half %x)`: Same as above, `%copysign.x`  │
│ is `poison`.\n2.  `%and = fcmp oeq half %copysign.x,         │
│ 0xH7C00`: The input `%copysign.x` is `poison`, so the result │
│ `%and` is `poison`.\n\nThe function incorrectly returns      │
│ `poison` for a NaN input. This is a miscompile because       │
│ `poison` can lead to undefined behavior downstream, whereas  │
│ the original code produced a well-defined `false`.\n\n### 2. │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log reveals a two-step    │
│ transformation process that leads to the final incorrect     │
│ IR:\n\n1.  **First Transformation**:\n    ```\n    IC: Old = │
│ %cmp = fcmp uge half %copysign.x, 0xH7C00\n        New =     │
│ <badref> = fcmp ueq half %copysign.x, 0xH7C00\n    ```\n     │
│ This happens in `visitFCmpInst`. The `fcmp uge` is changed   │
│ to `fcmp ueq`. This is based on the logic that if `fabs(x)   │
│ >= +inf`, then `fabs(x)` must be equal to `+inf`. This is    │
│ valid for non-NaN values.\n\n2.  **Second                    │
│ Transformation**:\n    ```\n    IC: Replacing   %and =       │
│ select i1 %ord, i1 %cmp, i1 false\n        with   %1 = fcmp  │
│ oeq half %copysign.x, 0xH7C00\n    ```\n    This step        │
│ combines `select i1 (fcmp ord %x, 0), (fcmp ueq (fabs %x),   │
│ +inf), false` into `fcmp oeq (fabs %x), +inf`. This          │
│ transformation is valid if `fabs` does not have the `nnan`   │
│ flag. However, with `nnan`, if `%x` is NaN, `fabs(%x)` is    │
│ `poison`, and the logic breaks down as shown above.\n\nThe   │
│ root of the problem lies in the first transformation. It     │
│ incorrectly simplifies `uge` to `ueq` without considering    │
│ that the operand might be `poison` due to the `nnan` flag on │
│ the `fabs` operation.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe   │
│ first transformation from `fcmp uge` to `fcmp ueq` is        │
│ performed by a specific optimization in                      │
│ `InstCombineCompares.cpp`. The debugger points to            │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp:846 │
│ 5`. This is inside a `switch` statement that handles         │
│ different `fcmp` predicates when one of the operands is      │
│ `+inf`.\n\n```cpp\n//                                        │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp:8465 │
│ \ncase FCmpInst::FCMP_UGE:\n  return new                     │
│ FCmpInst(FCmpInst::FCMP_UEQ, Op0, Op1, \"\",                 │
│ &I);\n```\n\nThis code is part of a larger block that        │
│ simplifies comparisons with infinity. The logic is that for  │
│ any floating-point value `v`, `v >= +inf` is equivalent to   │
│ `v == +inf`. This holds true for numbers and `-inf`.         │
│ However, it doesn't account for the unordered case with      │
│ NaNs. `uge` is true if unordered, while `ueq` is also true   │
│ if unordered. The issue arises from the interaction with     │
│ `nnan`.\n\nThe `nnan` flag on `fabs` means we can assume the │
│ input to `fabs` is not a NaN. If it is, the result is        │
│ `poison`. The `fcmp` simplification does not account for its │
│ operand being `poison`. When `%copysign.x` is `poison`,      │
│ `fcmp uge poison, +inf` is `poison`, but the original logic  │
│ would have produced `false` due to the `fcmp ord`            │
│ check.\n\nThe transformation from `(select (fcmp ord x, 0),  │
│ (fcmp uge (fabs x), +inf), false)` to `(fcmp oeq (fabs x),   │
│ +inf)` is the final step that causes the miscompile, but it  │
│ relies on the intermediate `fcmp ueq` form. The core issue   │
│ is that these transformations are not safe when `fabs` has   │
│ `nnan`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to    │
│ prevent the initial `uge` to `ueq` simplification if the     │
│ operand of the `fcmp` comes from an instruction with the     │
│ `nnan` flag. This is a conservative but safe                 │
│ approach.\n\n**File**:                                       │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp`\n* │
│ *Lines**: 8465-8465\n**Proposed Edit**:\nReplace:\n```cpp\n  │
│ return new FCmpInst(FCmpInst::FCMP_UEQ, Op0, Op1, \"\",      │
│ &I);\n```\nWith:\n```cpp\n      // This is unsafe if Op0 has │
│ the nnan flag, as it can be poison.\n      if (auto *O =     │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op0))\n        if (O->hasNoNaNs())\n   │
│ break;\n      return new FCmpInst(FCmpInst::FCMP_UEQ, Op0,   │
│ Op1, \"\", &I);\n```\nThis change checks if the operand      │
│ `Op0` is an instruction and if it has the `nnan` flag        │
│ (`hasNoNaNs()`). If so, it skips the optimization by         │
│ breaking from the switch case.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe   │
│ miscompilation is caused by an overly aggressive             │
│ optimization in `InstCombine` that simplifies `fcmp uge X,   │
│ +inf` to `fcmp ueq X, +inf`. This transformation is          │
│ incorrect when `X` can be `poison`, which happens in the     │
│ reproducer because `X` is the result of an `llvm.fabs` call  │
│ with the `nnan` flag on a NaN input.\n\nThe proposed fix is  │
│ to disable this specific transformation when the operand of  │
│ the `fcmp` has the `nnan` flag. This prevents the incorrect  │
│ simplification and ensures that the subsequent               │
│ transformations, which rely on this incorrect form, are not  │
│ triggered. This will resolve the bug and ensure correct code │
│ generation for this and similar cases."})                    │
